[Fact:adamEasterEgg:Programmer's hidden signature]
At #R34000, between the music engine routines, there are four bytes with ASCII
values #N97, #N100, #N97, #N109 -- the word ADAM. This code is completely unreachable
at runtime; no code path can ever reach it. No member of the development team is known as Adam, and at the time of disassembly, the reason for including it as a signature in the game was unknown. Perhaps a programmer's nickname? A family member's name? Perhaps a reference to Masters of the Universe?

[Fact:deadJumpInMusicEngine:A jump that never jumps]
At #R34004, inside the music engine, there is a JR Z,#N34004 instruction -- a
conditional branch that would jump to itself. However, the Z flag is always
clear when execution reaches that point, so the branch never fires. It is dead
code that does nothing.

[Fact:unusedWalkOutAnimation:The winner's exit animation that never plays]
Both #R37714 (P1 wins) and #R37748 (P2 wins) contain unreachable blocks that
would have applied the animation 35 (walk-out animation). However it is completely unreachable: they execute a JP or JR
immediately beforehand and never return. In other systems this animation is executed, showing the winner walking out of the arena.

[Fact:selfPatchingInvulnerability:The game patches itself to enable damage]
A RET Z instruction inside #R39371 prevents P1 from losing energy, keeping them
invulnerable during the demo/attract mode. When the player starts a real match,
routines #R36212 and #R36508 overwrite that byte in memory with a NOP, removing
the protection. The same pair of routines also rewrites the menu text from
"0 DEMO" to "START GAME". Once this routines are executed we can't no longer launch the demo mode.

[Fact:unusedMusicLoopPointers:Music loop pointers that are never written]
The music engine state area at #R33864 reserves two 2-byte slots for loop-back
addresses: Melody loop pointer at #R33869 and Bass loop pointer at #R33873. In the final
version neither is ever written to. The restart mechanism instead reads the
loop address inline from the music data stream at #R33903. The slots are a
leftover from an earlier design.

[Fact:unusedBossTilesInEnemyBank:Unused final boss]
The enemy and head sprite bank at #R40192 contains the complete tiles of Drax and Mariana with no runtime
caller. No sprite frame definition references these indices and
no movement applies them during gameplay. At #R46871 there are 16 bytes of tile sequence data corresponding to the spell
projectile animation for Drax, alternating tile IDs 18 and 22 from the
head sprite bank. No runtime code references this data. They are remnants of the final boss cut in this part.

[Fact:unusedStateBuffer:An unused buffer initialised to 6]
At #R46825 there are 2 bytes. The first is always 0, written redundantly by
#R37866. The second, at #N46826, retains its initialisation value of 6 and is
neither read nor written at any point. It is likely a remnant from when the P2
overlay state block had 9 fields and the IY+8 slot was later removed.

[Fact:fontDataOverwrittenByFramebuffer:Font data overwritten by the framebuffer]
From #R26480 onwards there are UDG font table entries that were loaded as part
of the main code block but are never referenced at runtime. The framebuffer,
which spans #R24066 to #N26751, overwrites them during normal gameplay.

[Fact:ivtOverwritesTile0:The interrupt vector table overwrites the first byte of tile 0]
The interrupt vector table generator at #R38494 writes 257 bytes of value 0xF0
starting from address #N48896. The 257th byte lands exactly at #N49152, the first byte of the barbarian sprite tileset. After startup that byte
holds #N$F0 rather than the original #N0. Because tile 0 is the fully
transparent blank tile and its header byte is not read by any rendering path
once the game is running, the change has no visible effect.

[Fact:xDeltaOverwritesUnusedTiles:The X-delta table and the ISR overwrites two unused sprite tiles]
At startup, #R48935 copies 100 bytes from #R49046 (the per-frame horizontal
displacement table) to address #N61568. This area corresponds to tiles
194 and 195 in the barbarian sprite bank.
In the other hand, #R49031 writes the 46-byte ISR code -- relocated from #R38500 -- to
address #N61680. This address falls inside tiles 195 and 196 of the
barbarian sprite bank (#N$F0C0-#N$F0FF). Those tiles are unused: no sprite
definition references either index.

[Fact:p2SpriteCompositing:P2 is rendered by compositing one overlay tile on top of the shared P1 sprite]
P1 and P2 share an identical base sprite bank at #R49152. Rather than
maintaining a full duplicate tileset for P2, the game renders P2 using the
same 4x3 tile grid as P1 and then composites a single extra tile on top each
frame via #R38220. The overlay tile index is read from #R47223, and its
framebuffer position from #R47329, both indexed by the current P2 frame
counter at #R46442. The tile is sourced from the secondary sprite bank at
#R40192, which holds the P2-specific head variants and overlay graphics.
To avoid duplicating renderer logic, #R38220 populates the overlay state
block at #R46817 using the same 9-byte layout as the flying head block at
#R46809, allowing #R38103 and #R38158 to serve both paths without
modification.

[Fact:devBuildStamp:A hidden build stamp is accessible from the main menu]
Pressing key 3 on the main menu does not launch a game mode. Instead,
#R36130 loads the address #R48662 into DE and draws the string "FINAL V8
5>11>87" over the SELECT OPTION line via #R36022, then loops straight back
to the animation and key-wait cycle. The string remains on screen until
the player presses another key.
This is is consistent with a build tag left by the developer: version 8, dated 5 November 1987.